{"title_page": "Palaiologos", "text_new": "{{Infobox noble house\n|surname=Palaiologos\n|native_name=\u03a0\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2\n|other_name=Palaeologus, Palaeologue\n|coat_of_arms=File:Byzantine Eagle.svg\n|coat_of_arms_size=150px\n|caption=[[Double-headed eagle]] with the family cypher\n|type=[[Royal family|Imperial Family]]\n|country=[[Byzantine Empire under the Palaiologos dynasty|Byzantine Empire]]<br>[[Despotate of the Morea]]<br>[[Duchy of Montferrat]]\n|titles=* [[List of Byzantine emperors|Byzantine Emperor]]\n* [[Despotate of the Morea|Despot of the Morea]]\n* [[List of rulers of Montferrat|Marquess of Montferrat]]\n|founded={{Start date|11th century}}<br>1259 <small>(as Imperial Family)</small>\n|founder=[[Nikephoros Palaiologos]] {{Small|(first known)}}<br>[[Michael VIII Palaiologos]] <small>(first emperor)</small>\n|final ruler=[[Constantine XI Palaiologos]] (Byzantine Empire)<br>[[Thomas Palaiologos]] (Morea)<br>[[Margaret Paleologa]] (Montferrat)\n|dissolution=1453 (Byzantine rule)<br>1460 (rule in the Morea)<br>1536 (Montferrat cadet branch)\n|traditions=[[Eastern Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodoxy]] (predominantly; 11th century\u20131460)<br>[[Roman Catholicism]] (Montferrat lineage and lineage in exile)\n}}\n\nThe '''Palaiologos''' ({{small|[[plural|pl.]]}}&nbsp;'''Palaiologoi'''; {{lang-grc-gre|\u03a0\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2}}, <small>pl.</small> {{lang|grc|\u03a0\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03b9}}), also found in English-language literature as '''Palaeologus''' or '''Palaeologue''', was the name of a [[Byzantine Greeks|Byzantine Greek]]<ref>[[Alexander A. Vasiliev|Vasiliev, Aleksandr A.]] (1964). ''History of the Byzantine Empire''. '''2'''. [[Univ of Wisconsin Press]]. p. 583. {{ISBN|9780299809263}}. <q>The dynasty of the Palaeologi belonged to a very well known Greek family which, beginning with the first Comneni, gave Byzantium many energetic and gifted men, especially in the military field.</q></ref> family, which rose to nobility and ultimately produced the last ruling dynasty of the [[Byzantine Empire under the Palaiologos dynasty|Byzantine Empire]].\n\nFounded by the 11th-century general [[Nikephoros Palaiologos]] and his son [[George Palaiologos|George]], the family rose to the highest aristocratic circles through its marriage into the [[Doukas]] and [[Komnenos]] dynasties. After the [[Fourth Crusade]], members of the family fled to the neighboring [[Empire of Nicaea]], ruled by the [[Laskaris]] family, where [[Michael VIII Palaiologos]] became senior co-emperor to the young [[John IV Laskaris]] in 1259. In 1261, forces loyal to Michael recaptured [[Constantinople]], which had been under the occupation of the [[Latin Empire]] since the Fourth Crusade sacked the city in 1204, and Michael VIII was crowned in the Hagia Sophia as sole emperor.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gill|first=Joseph|year=1980|title=Family feuds in fourteenth century Byzantium: Palaeologi and Cantacuzeni|url=http://dmr.bsu.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/ConspectusH&CISOPTR=554&REC=1|journal=Conspectus of History|publisher=[[Ball State University]]|volume=1|issue=5|page=64}}</ref> For the next 192 years, Michael's descendants ruled the Byzantine Empire until the death of [[Constantine XI Palaiologos]] and the [[Fall of Constantinople]] at the hands of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] on May 29, 1453, becoming the longest-lived dynasty in Byzantine history.\n\nFollowing the fall of Constantinople, members of the family scattered. One branch of the family, descended from Emperor [[Andronikos II Palaiologos|Andronikos II]], had ruled the [[Duchy of Montferrat]] in Italy as feudal lords since 1306 and continued to do so until its extinction in 1536. Some Palaiologoi attained prominent positions within Ottoman society in the decades following Constantinople's fall. The surviving brothers of the final emperor Constantine XI; [[Demetrios Palaiologos|Demetrios]] and [[Thomas Palaiologos]], quarreled over who was the rightful heir to the empire, their last certain descendants with the Palaiologos name died in the 16th century, although one branch with alleged, but uncertain, descent from Thomas survived until the 17th century in Barbados and England.\n\nNot all who bore the name Palaiologos were closely related to the imperial line, even in Byzantine times, and in the centuries following Constantinople's fall, many Palaiologoi spread out across Europe, mainly settling in Italy or choosing to remain in the Ottoman Empire. The last name, and variations of it, remains in use in Greece and elsewhere, although connections between any living Palaiologoi and the old imperial dynasty cannot be confidently established.\n\n== Origins ==\nThe origins of the Palaiologoi (<small>{{abbr|lit.|Literally}}</small>&nbsp;\"old word\", sometimes glossed as \"ragman\"<ref>{{cite dictionary|last=Kazhdan|first=Alexander P.|author-link=Alexander P. Kazhdan|title=Palaiologos|dictionary=[[Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium]]|volume=III|page=1557|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford|year=1991|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/abstract/10.1093/acref/9780195046526.001.0001/acref-9780195046526-e-4026|isbn=9780195046526|doi=10.1093/acref/9780195046526.001.0001}}</ref> or \"antique collector\"<ref name=\"van\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x7a1cRMNz3UC&pg=PA129|title=\u00c9tudes prosopographiques|last=Vannier|first=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|publisher=Publications de la Sorbonne|year=1986|isbn=9782859441104|editor-last=Cheynet|editor-first=Jean-Claude|location=Paris|page=129|chapter=Les premiers Pal\u00e9ologues. \u00c9tude g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique et prosopographique}}</ref>) are unknown. Later traditions sometimes tied them to the [[Medieval Italy|Italian]] city of [[Viterbo]] (the [[Latin]] ''vetus verbum'', a dubious etymology of the town's name, having the same meaning as the family's name) or to the [[Ancient Romans|Romans]] who immigrated east with [[Constantine the Great]] during the founding of [[Constantinople|his new capital]].<ref name=\"van\" /> Both were probably fabrications created to help legitimize the dynasty.<ref name=\"enchel\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://asiaminor.ehw.gr/Forms/fLemmaBody.aspx?lemmaid=11799|title=Palaeologan Dynasty (1259-1453)|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of the Hellenic World|location=Asia Minor|publisher=Foundation of the Hellenic World|year=2008|access-date=15 October 2014}}</ref> The family are first attested as local lords in [[Asia Minor]], particularly [[Anatolikon]],<ref name=\"van\" /> with [[Nikephoros Palaiologos]] (died 1081) rising to command over [[Mesopotamia (theme)|Mesopotamia]] under [[Michael VII Doukas]]. He supported the revolt of [[Nikephoros III Botaneiates]], while his son [[George Palaiologos|George]] married Anna Doukaina and therefore supported his [[Irene Doukaina|sister-in-law]]'s husband [[Alexios I Komnenos|Alexios Komnenos]] during his rise to power.<ref name=\"enchel\" /> As commander (''doux'') of [[Durr\u00ebs|Dyrrhachium]], George faced the [[Norman Italy|Norman]] [[List of Counts and Dukes of Apulia and Calabria|Duke]] [[Robert Guiscard]] in [[Battle of Dyrrhachium (1081)|battle]].\n\nThe Palaiologoi held military offices and further united their family to the Doukai and Komnenoi during the 12th century.<ref name=\"enchel\" /> They followed [[Theodore I Laskaris|Theodore Laskaris]] to [[Nicaea]] and began to assume high-ranking political offices as well. During the 13th century, the Palaiologoi continued to increase in prestige following their various marriages with prominent Byzantine families and their active role within the [[Empire of Nicaea]], one of the Byzantine successor states founded after the crusaders of the [[Fourth Crusade]] captured Constantinople and established the [[Latin Empire]]. [[Alexios Palaiologos (Despot)|Alexios Palaiologos]] (died 1203) married a granddaughter of Zoe Doukaina (youngest daughter of [[Constantine X Doukas]]) and her husband [[Adrianos Komnenos]] (younger brother of Emperor Alexios I). Another Alexios Palaiologos married Irene Angelina, eldest daughter of [[Alexios III Angelos]] and [[Euphrosyne Doukaina Kamatera]]. The latter couple's daughter Theodora Palaiologina married her cousin [[Andronikos Palaiologos (megas domestikos)|Andronikos Palaiologos]] (c. 1190\u20131248/52), who was descended from Zoe. The couple were the progenitors of the imperial dynasty. Their son was Emperor [[Michael VIII Palaiologos]] (1223\u20131282).\n\nThe fact that the Palaiologoi were descended from most of the major Byzantine dynasties was reflected in their choice of presenting their names. For instance, Michael VIII Palaiologos referred to himself as ''Michael Komnenos Doukas Angelos Palaiologos''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eaOeDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=Michael+Komnenos+Doukas+Angelos+Palaiologos#v=onepage&q=Michael%20Komnenos%20Doukas%20Angelos%20Palaiologos&f=false|title=The Byzantine Hellene: The Life of Emperor Theodore Laskaris and Byzantium in the Thirteenth Century|last=Angelov|first=Dimiter|date=2019|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781108480710|location=|pages=121|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Imperial line ==\n\n=== Palaiologoi emperors ===\n{{See also|Byzantine Empire under the Palaiologos dynasty|Fall of Constantinople}}\n[[File:Michael VIII Palaiologos (head).jpg|left|thumb|[[Michael VIII Palaiologos]] (r. 1259\u20131282), the first [[Byzantine emperor|Byzantine Emperor]] of the Palaiologos dynasty. Miniature from the manuscript of [[George Pachymeres|Pachymeres]]' ''Historia'', 14th century.]]\n[[File:Byzantine imperial flag, 14th century.svg|thumb|Flag of the [[Byzantine Empire]] adopted by the Palaiologos dynasty, featuring the [[tetragrammatic cross]]]]\nUnder the rule of the Palaiologoi (1259\u20131453), the fragmented [[Byzantine Empire]] still considered themselves to be the [[Roman Empire]], but began to focus more on the empire's [[Greeks|Greek]] heritage than previous dynasties had. The word \"[[Hellene]]\" began to be used more frequently than before to describe themselves, after having been seen as a synonym for \"[[pagan]]\" for many centuries. The dynasty was a patron of literature and the arts; among others, [[George Gemistos Plethon]] came to prominence. The [[hesychasm]] controversy also took place during the rule of the Palaiologoi dynasty.\n\nAt the later days of their empire the [[Peloponnese]] was the largest and wealthiest part of the empire, and was ruled as the [[Despotate of Morea]] by members of the Palaiologos family, often two or three younger brothers simultaneously. Although they often squabbled amongst themselves they were usually fiercely loyal to the emperor in Constantinople (though sometimes they sought to supplant the emperor and rise to the throne), while their land was surrounded by hostile [[Republic of Venice|Venetians]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]]. The capital of the despotate was [[Mystras]], a large fortress built by the Palaiologoi near [[Sparta]].\n\nThe Palaiologoi twice attempted to reunite the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]] with the [[Roman Catholic Church]], hoping this would lead the West to give them aid against the Turks. The first attempt was at the [[Second Council of Lyons]] in 1274 under [[Michael VIII Palaiologos]] and the second in 1438-39 under [[John VIII Palaiologos]] at the [[Council of Ferrara-Florence]]. Every attempt at reunification was strongly opposed by the regular clergy and the general population.\n[[File:Manuel II Paleologus.jpg|thumb|Emperor [[Manuel II Palaiologos]] (r. 1391\u20131425)]]\nAfter having been reduced in size due to outside invasion and internal civil war, the Byzantine Empire of the 15th century had shrunk to the cities of Constantinople, [[Thessaloniki|Thessalonica]] and [[Despotate of the Morea|the Morea]]. Thessalonica fell in the 1430s and Constantonople was eventually [[Fall of Constantinople|captured]] by the Ottoman sultan [[Mehmed II]] on 29 May 1453, with the final Emperor, [[Constantine XI Palaiologos]], dying in the fighting.\n\n==== Dynastic genealogy ====\n[[File:Constantine XI Palaiologos miniature (cropped).jpg|thumb|Emperor [[Constantine XI Palaiologos]] (r. 1449\u20131453), the final Byzantine Emperor]]\nMichael VIII's son [[Andronikos II Palaiologos]] (1259\u20131332) married [[Anna of Hungary (Byzantine empress)|Anne of Hungary]] and fathered [[Michael IX Palaiologos|Michael Palaiologos]] (1277\u20131320), sometimes numbered the ninth. Michael IX married [[Rita of Armenia]]. Their son, the grandson of Andronikos II, was [[Andronikos III Palaiologos]] (1297\u20131341). Andronikos III married [[Anna of Savoy]]. Their son was [[John V Palaiologos]] (1332\u20131391). John V married [[Helena Kantakouzene]], a daughter of his co-ruler [[John VI Kantakouzenos]]. Their sons included [[Andronikos IV Palaiologos]] (1348\u20131385) and [[Manuel II Palaiologos]] (1350\u20131425). Manuel II married [[Helena Draga\u0161]]. They were the parents of [[John VIII Palaiologos]] (1392\u20131448) and [[Constantine XI Palaiologos]] (1404\u20131453), the last [[Byzantine emperor]], as well as the despots of Morea [[Demetrios Palaiologos]] (1407\u20131470) and [[Thomas Palaiologos]] (1409\u20131465).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Reign\n!Relation\n|-\n|[[Michael VIII Palaiologos]]\n|1259\u20131282\n|\n|-\n|[[Andronikos II Palaiologos]]\n|1282\u20131328\n|Son of Michael VIII\n|-\n|[[Michael IX Palaiologos]]\n|1295\u20131320; <small>''with'' Andronikos II</small>\n|Son of Andronikos II\n|-\n|[[Andronikos III Palaiologos]]\n|1328\u20131341\n|Son of Michael IX\n|-\n|[[John V Palaiologos]]\n|1341\u20131376; <small>''with'' [[John VI Kantakouzenos]] 1347\u20131379</small><br>1379\u20131390<br>1390\u20131391\n|Son of Andronikos III\n|-\n|[[Andronikos IV Palaiologos]]\n|1376\u20131379\n|Son of John V\n|-\n|[[John VII Palaiologos]]\n|1390<br>1403\u20131408; <small>as \"Emperor of All Thessaly\"</small>\n|Son of Andronikos IV\n|-\n|[[Manuel II Palaiologos]]\n|1391\u20131425\n|Son of John V\n|-\n|[[Andronikos V Palaiologos]]\n|1403\u20131407; <small>with John VII in Thessaly</small>\n|Son of John VII\n|-\n|[[John VIII Palaiologos]]\n|1425\u20131448\n|Son of Manuel II\n|-\n|[[Constantine XI Palaiologos]]\n|1449\u20131453\n|Son of Manuel II\n|}\n\n=== Later history ===\n[[File:Thomas Palaiologos2.jpg|left|thumb|Contemporary painting of [[Thomas Palaiologos]] (1471) at [[Ancona]] in Italy. Thomas was the brother of emperors [[John VIII Palaiologos|John VIII]] and [[Constantine XI Palaiologos|Constantine XI]] and ancestor of later surviving members of the imperial Palaiologos line.]]\nAfter the fall of Constantinople and the death of Constantine XI, his two surviving brothers (and the co-Despots of the Morea) Demetrios and Thomas both claimed the title of emperor and civil war erupted in the Morea. In 1460, Demetrios called on sultan Mehmed II for aid, but the plan backfired as Mehmed proceeded to conquer the despotate.<ref name=\":3\">[[Steven Runciman|Runciman, Steven]] (2009). ''Lost Capital of Byzantium: The History of Mistra and the Peloponnese.'' Tauris Parke Paperbacks. {{ISBN|978-1-84511-895-2}}. p. 83.</ref> Although Thomas had sought aid from both the Pope and the [[Republic of Genoa]] against Demetrios and the Ottomans, little of this support had materialised. Demetrios and his wife Theodora were allowed to remain in the Ottoman Empire as subjects of the Sultan and Demetrios was even given the town of [[Enez|Ainos]] in [[Thrace]], as well as parts of the islands of [[Thasos]] and [[Samothrace]], as an [[appanage]]. A few years later, possibly due to attempting to cheat tax officials, Demetrios, his wife and his daughter Helena fell out of the Sultan's favor and lived the rest of their lives in poverty. Demetrios eventually retired to a monastery, taking the monastic name David, and died in 1470.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThomas had first fled to [[Corfu]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=The fall of Constantinople, 1453.|last=Runciman, Steven, 1903-2000.|date=1965|publisher=University Press|isbn=9781107604698|location=Cambridge|pages=171|oclc=220712}}</ref> but later moved to Rome where he made a ceremonial entrance as Emperor of Constantinople on March 7, 1461. Thomas continued to live in Rome for the rest of his life and was officially recognized as the legitimate Emperor of Constantinople by Pope [[Pius II]]. To create greater support for his cause, Thomas officially changed his religion from Greek Orthodoxy to Roman Catholicism. Thomas actually hoped to regain his lost lands. When preparations were being made for a crusade to take Constantinople in the 1460s, Thomas toured Italy in order to raise sympathy and support, though no crusade successfully materialised.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Harris|first=Jonathan|date=2013|title=Despots, Emperors, and Balkan Identity in Exile|journal=The Sixteenth Century Journal|volume=44|issue=3|pages=643\u2013661|issn=0361-0160|jstor=24244808}}</ref>\n\nAfter Thomas's death in 1465 his oldest son [[Andreas Palaiologos]] (born 1453) continued claiming the position of Emperor. Andreas and his brother [[Manuel Palaiologos|Manuel]] had continued to live in Corfu and did not see their father again until the last few days before Thomas died. After that, Andreas lived in Rome, also with support for his claim as the heir of the eastern imperial throne.<ref name=\":4\">Norwich, John Julius, ''Byzantium - The Decline and Fall'', p.446</ref> Andreas repeatedly overspent the money donated to him by the Pope (which perhaps was only enough for a meager lifestyle) and married Caterina a \"lady from the streets of Rome\".<ref name=\":5\">Runciman, Steven, 1903-2000. (1965). ''The fall of Constantinople, 1453''. Cambridge,: University Press. p.&nbsp;184. {{ISBN|9781107604698}}. {{OCLC|220712}}.</ref>\n[[File:\u03a3\u03c6\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03af\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c5.png|thumb|Seal of [[Andreas Palaiologos]] in Western style, with the imperial [[double-headed eagle]] on an [[Escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]] and the Latin inscription \"Andreas Palaiologos, [[by the Grace of God]], [[Despot (court title)|Despot]] of the [[Rhomaioi]]\".]]\nAndreas did travel across Europe in search for powerful rulers who might aid him in reclaiming Constantinople and the imperial throne but there were none that would support him. In the late summer of 1481, Andreas gathered funds and support in southern Italy in order to attack the Ottomans, hoping that a great civil war would occur in the empire due to the death of Mehmed II. When this did not happen, Andreas called off the attack.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nDesperate for money, Andreas sold the rights to the Byzantine crown twice; first to [[Charles VIII of France]] in 1494 and then to [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]] and [[Isabella I of Castile]] around the year 1500.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> It is doubtful that he ever received the money owed as his widow had to beg the Pope for money to pay for his funeral after he died in poverty on April 7, 1502.<ref name=\":5\" /> Although it is uncertain if Andreas ever had children, Donald M. Nicol's ''The Immortal Emperor'' recognises Constantine Palaiologos, who served in the Papal Guard, and a woman named Maria, who married the Russian noble Vasily Mikhailovich, as possible children of Andreas.<ref>Donald M. Nicol, ''The Immortal Emperor'', Cambridge University Press, 1992, pp.&nbsp;115\u201322. {{ISBN|0-521-41456-3}}. p. 116.</ref> An illegitimate daughter of Constantine Palaiologos is present in some Italian sources; she is identified as Domitia or Dominique, the concubine of Evandro Conti (a Roman nobleman descendant of the family of [[Pope Innocent III]]) and mother of his illegitimate children: Mario (or Marzio, ''Mars'') and Giulia.  Mario Conti was [[Knights Hospitaller|Knight of Malta]]; who died during the [[Great Siege of Malta]], in the defense of Fort St. Elmo, in 1565, without descendants. His sister, Giulia Conti, was a nun in the monastery of Saints Simeon and Jude, in [[Viterbo]], under the name of ''Sister Stefania''.\n\nIn an effort to reunite the Catholic Church and the Orthodox Church, [[Pope Paul II]] arranged during 1472 a marriage between the Catholic daughter of Thomas Palaiologos, [[Sophia Paleologue|Zoe Palaiologina]] (renamed Sophia), and Grand Prince [[Ivan III of Russia]], with the hope of making Russia a Roman Catholic country. Though the attempt to join the churches failed, the marriage became one of the building blocks from which Moscow could in later centuries claim to be the \"[[third Rome]]\" (after the first Rome, Rome, and the second Rome, Constantinople).<ref>Nicol, Donald MacGillivray, Last Centuries of Byzantium, 1261\u20131453, Cambridge University Press, Second Edition, 1993, p. 72</ref> Sophia was visited in both 1480 and 1491 by her brother Andreas, who both times begged her for money.\n\n== Line in Montferrat ==\n{{further|List of rulers of Montferrat#Paleologo dynasty}}[[File:Portrait believed to depict Margherita Paleologo by Giulio Romano.jpg|thumb|Portrait of [[Margaret Paleologa]], the final Palaiologos to rule Montferrat (r. 1533\u20131536)]]\nA [[Theodore I, Marquess of Montferrat|younger son]] of Emperor Andronikos II, [[Theodore I (Marquess of Montferrat)|Theodore]], became lord of [[Montferrat]] in 1306 as heir of his mother. His feudal dynasty ruled in Montferrat until 1536, longer than the imperial branch did in Constantinople. This inheritance was eventually incorporated by marriage to the [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] family, rulers of the [[Duchy of Mantua]], who descend from the Palaiologoi of Montferrat. Later, that succession passed to the [[Dukes of Lorraine]], whose later head became the progenitor of the [[Habsburg-Lorraine]] emperors of [[Austria]].\n\nThe Paleologo-Oriundi, an extant line, descends from Flaminio, an illegitimate son of the last Palaiologos marquess [[John George, Marquess of Montferrat|John George]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cassano|first=Gian Paolo|date=July 2017|title=Organo di informazione del Circolo Culturale \"I Marchesi del Monferrato\" \"in attesa di registrazione in Tribunale\"|url=http://www.marchesimonferrato.com/web2007/_resources/16.pdf|journal=Bollettino del Marchesato|publisher=[[Cassa di Risparmio di Alessandria]]|volume=3|issue=16|pages=3\u20139|access-date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Name\n!Reign\n!Relation\n|-\n|[[Theodore I (Marquess of Montferrat)|Theodore I]]\n|1306\u20131338\n|Son of Emperor Andronikos II\n|-\n|[[John II, Marquess of Montferrat|John II]]\n|1338\u20131372\n|Son of Theodore I\n|-\n|[[Secondotto, Marquess of Montferrat|Secondotto]]\n|1372\u20131378\n|Son of John II\n|-\n|[[John III, Marquess of Montferrat|John III]]\n|1378\u20131381\n|Son of John II\n|-\n|[[Theodore II, Marquess of Montferrat|Theodore II]]\n|1381\u20131418\n|Son of John II\n|-\n|[[John Jacob, Marquess of Montferrat|John Jacob]]\n|1418\u20131445\n|Son of Theodore II\n|-\n|[[John IV, Marquess of Montferrat|John IV]]\n|1445\u20131464\n|Son of John Jacob\n|-\n|[[William VIII, Marquess of Montferrat|William VIII]]\n|1464\u20131483\n|Son of John Jacob\n|-\n|[[Boniface III, Marquess of Montferrat|Boniface III]]\n|1483\u20131494\n|Son of John Jacob\n|-\n|[[William IX, Marquess of Montferrat|William IX]]\n|1494\u20131518\n|Son of Boniface III\n|-\n|[[Boniface IV, Marquess of Montferrat|Boniface IV]]\n|1518\u20131530\n|Son of William IX\n|-\n|[[John George, Marquess of Montferrat|John George]]\n|1530\u20131533\n|Son of Boniface III\n|-\n|[[Margaret Paleologa|Margaret]]\n|1533\u20131536\n|Daughter of William IX\n|}\n\n== Palaiologoi in Cornwall and Barbados ==\n[[File:Tombstone_of_Teodoro_Paleologus.png|left|thumb|Tombstone of [[Theodore Palaiologos (16th century)|Theodore Palaiologos]] (~1560\u20131636). It begins with proclaiming that ''Here lies the body of Theodoro Paleologus of Pesaro in Italy, descendended from the Imperial line of the last Christian Emperors of Greece''.]][[File:Descendants of Manuel II Palaiologos.png|thumb|Genealogy of the Cornwall Palaiologoi as allegedly descended from Emperor [[Manuel II Palaiologos]] (r. 1391\u20131425)]]In the late 16th century, three Palaiologoi who claimed descent from Thomas Palaiologos through his son John lived in the town of [[Pesaro]] in Italy; a [[Theodore Palaiologos (16th century)|Theodore Palaiologos]] and his uncles Scipione and Leonidas Palaiologos.<ref name=\":02\" /> Their lineage is uncertain though, as there is no independent evidence that Thomas had a son by the name of John. If their claims to being descended from Thomas are false, the imperial Palaiologos line became extinct with the death of Andreas Palaiologos in 1502, or with the death of his potential son Constantine at some point in the 16th century.<ref>Nicol, Donald MacGillivray, Last Centuries of Byzantium, 1261\u20131453, Cambridge University Press, Second Edition, 1993</ref>\n\nAfter Theodore, Scipione and Leonidas were convicted of an attempted murder (for which Leonidas was executed), Theodore either chose or was forced to leave Italy.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Nicol|first=D. M.|date=1974-01-01|title=Byzantium and England|url=https://ojs.lib.uom.gr/index.php/BalkanStudies/article/view/1145|journal=Balkan Studies|language=en|volume=15|issue=2|pages=179\u2013203|issn=2241-1674}}</ref> In the early 17th century, Theodore worked as a soldier and an assassin in the service of [[Henry Clinton, 2nd Earl of Lincoln|Henry Clinton,]] the [[Earl of Lincoln]].<ref name=\":02\" /> At [[Tattershall Castle, Lincolnshire|Tattershall Castle]] (Clinton's estate), Theodore met the famous captain and explorer [[John Smith (explorer)|John Smith]] and gradually helped him return to society after he had retired into seclusion at the castle.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/29703/the-byzantines-of-cornwall/|title=The Byzantines of Cornwall {{!}} Neos Kosmos|last=Kalymniou|first=Dean|date=2015-04-20|website=English Edition|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.donne.me.uk/landulph/church.htm#Palaeologus|title=Landulph Parish Church|website=www.donne.me.uk|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> In 1600, Theodore married the daughter of the nobleman William Balls of [[Hadleigh, Suffolk]], Mary Balls, with whom he had several children. Theodore finally settled down in [[Landulph]], [[Cornwall]]. He died on the 21st of January 1636 and was buried that same year.<ref name=\":02\" />[[File:Tombstone_of_Ferdinando_Paleolocus.jpg|thumb|Monument commemorating the 1670 (the monument erroneously specifies the  year as 1678) death of [[Ferdinand Palaiologos]] in [[Barbados]]]]\nIn total, Theodore had seven children (four sons and three daughters) with Mary, although his first son, also called Theodore, died in infancy. One of his daughters died young and it is unlikely that the other two, Maria and Dorothea (died in 1674 and 1681 respectively),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RTZFAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA93&lpg=PA93&dq=Paleologey#v=onepage&q=Paleologey&f=false|title=Archaeologia, Or, Miscellaneous Tracts, Relating to Antiquity, Volym 18|last=|first=|publisher=|year=1817|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> had children as Maria likely never married and Dorothea only married at the age of fifty (to William Arundel, a man from Cornwall). Among his three surviving sons were another son named Theodore (born in 1609) who served as a Captain in the Parliamentarian army during the [[English Civil War]], dying in 1644 and being buried in [[Westminster Abbey]], a son named John Theodore Palaiologos (born in 1611) who is recorded to have lived in Barbados in his thirties and [[Ferdinand Palaiologos]] (born in 1619).<ref name=\":02\"/><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/abbey-commemorations/commemorations/theodore-palaeologus|title=Theodore Palaeologus|date=|website=Westminster Abbey|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\nFerdinand followed John Theodore to Barbados. They were some of the very first colonists to set foot on Barbados as it had only been discovered in 1620.<ref name=\":02\"/> John Theodore's eventual fate is unknown, no longer being mentioned in any source after 1644. Ferdinand stayed in Barbados and was known on the island as the \"Greek prince from Cornwall\". He married a woman called Rebecca Pomfrett with whom he had a son named Theodore, and died in October 1670.<ref name=\":02\"/><ref name=\":04\">{{Cite book|title=An Elizabethan Assassin: Theodore Paleologus: Seducer, Spy and Killer|last=Hall|first=John|publisher=The History Press|year=2015|isbn=978-0750962612|location=}}</ref> Perhaps the Imperial line of Palaiologoi never truly stopped dreaming of Constantinople; unlike the usual burial custom (feet to the west and head to the east), Ferdinand was buried with his head directly pointing towards the ancient capital. A monument with an inscription commemorating Ferdinand was erected near his grave in 1906.<ref name=\":02\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenationalherald.com/3741/ferdinando-paleologus-last-byzantine-emperor-in-western-hemisphere/|title=Ferdinando Paleologus: Last Byzantine Emperor in Western Hemisphere|date=2012-10-18|website=The National Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ludwell.org/new-world-grave-and-byzantine-emperors/|title=Byzantine Imperial Descendants in New World|date=2016-01-02|website=Ludwell.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\nFerdinand's son Theodore returned to Europe, at first working as a sailor in England and settling in [[Stepney]], [[London]] where he had a son and a [[Posthumous birth|posthumous]] daughter with his wife, a Martha Bradbury from Barbados. Theodore died in Spain at [[A Coru\u00f1a]] in 1693.<ref name=\":02\"/> If his son was still alive by then, he was not mentioned in his will, which was solely dedicated to his wife Martha.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Other Palaiologoi ==\n\n=== In the Ottoman Empire ===\n[[File:Signature of Khass Murad.png|left|thumb|Signature of [[Hass Murad Pasha]], an Ottoman statesman and possibly illegitimate son of one of [[Constantine XI Palaiologos]]'s brothers]]\nSome branches of the Palaiologoi remained in Ottoman Constantinople, and even prospered in the immediate post-conquest period. In the decades after 1453, Ottoman tax registers show a consortium of noble Greeks co-operating to bid for the lucrative [[tax farming]] district including Constantinople and the ports of western Anatolia. This group included names like \"Palologoz of Kassandros\" and \"Manuel Palologoz\".<ref name=\":6\">Papademetriou, Tom (2015). ''Render Unto the Sultan: Power, Authority, and the Greek Orthodox Church in the Early Ottoman Centuries''. Oxford: Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-871789-8}}. p. 190</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Vryonis|first=Speros|author-link=Speros Vryonis|year=1969|title=The Byzantine Legacy and Ottoman Forms|journal=[[Dumbarton Oaks Papers]]|publisher=Dumbarton Oaks, Trustees for [[Harvard University]]|volume=23/24|pages=251\u2013308|doi=10.2307/1291294|jstor=1291294|oclc=31601728}}</ref> This group stood in close contact with two powerful viziers, [[Mesih Pasha]] and [[Hass Murad Pasha]], both of whom were Palaiologoi and were force converted to Islam after the fall of Constantinople, as well as with other converted scions of Byzantine and Balkan aristocratic families like [[Mahmud Pasha Angelovi\u0107]], forming what the Ottomanist [[Halil \u0130nalc\u0131k]] termed a \"Greek faction\" at the court of Mehmed II.<ref name=\":6\" /> It is possibly that Mesih Pasha and Hass Murad Pasha were the illegitimate sons of one of Constantine XI Palaiologos's brothers.<ref>[[Franz Babinger|Babinger, Franz]] (1952). \"[http://www.islamicmanuscripts.info/REFERENCE/books/Hartmann-1952-Festschrift/Hartmann-1952-Festschrift-13-Babinger-197-210.pdf Eine Verf\u00fcgung des Pal\u00e4ologen Chass Murad-Pasa von Mitte Regeb 876 = Dez./Jan. 1471-72]\" (PDF). ''Documenta Islamica Inedita'' (in German). Berlin: Akademie-Verlag. pp. 197\u2013210.</ref>\n\n=== In Christian Europe ===\nDespite the fact that the imperial line established by Michal VIII Palaiologos likely died out at some point in the 16th or 17th century, contenders for the imperial Byzantine title emerged multiple times in different parts of Europe for several centuries. The family Palaiologos had already been quite widespread during the late Byzantine Empire and not all who bore the name were closely related to the imperial line. Acting as a penniless refugee from Byzantium, the name Palaiologos could lend whoever bore it prestige, if not monetary support from a prince, a pope or a cardinal. Many such Palaiologoi settled in Venice and other parts of Italy.<ref name=\":02\"/>\n\nSeveral such Palaiologoi served as [[cavalrymen]] in the service of the [[Republic of Venice]]. Among well-documented Palaiologoi were a Teodoro Paleologo, likely originally from [[Mystras]], who died in 1532,<ref>''[https://condottieridiventura.it/teodoro-paleologo-greco/ Teodoro Paleologo greco].'' Accessed on 5 May 2019(Italian).</ref> a Giovanni around 1482, Annibale Paleologus and his son Laeziniano around 1586, a Lucio Andronico Paleologo at the beginning of the 16th century and an Andrea Paleologo Graitzas around 1460. A large number of people with the last name Palaiologos (or variations thereof) living in Athens today still claim descent from this Andrea Paleologo Graitzas.<ref name=\":02\"/>\n\nThe use of titles and claims, even fake ones, by people from the Balkans also served as a way to remind the Western Europeans of the suffering that the people of the east had endured, thus becoming a means to earn sympathy and trust. Furthermore, if you were of noble birth it was likelier that you would be treated well. There was a \"Michael Palaiologos\" in Rome in 1505, who managed to convince Pope Julius II to send letters to the kings of Western Europe in the hope of raising ransom money so that Michael could pay the Ottomans for the release of his wife and children. Michael claimed to be related (in various ways) to the \"Duke of Constantinople\". Even though \"Palaiologos\" might have been his real last name, he was likely not closely related to the imperial line. Although successful in convincing the Pope and travelling northern Europe with Latin translations of the Pope's letter, he had little success in raising further sympathy. When he reached [[Turnhout]] in [[Flanders]], Michael was accused of being an impostor and promptly imprisoned, after which nothing more is known of his fate.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe Palaiologos dynasty had a lasting impact on the Greeks through the centuries of Ottoman rule, having been the last to govern independent Greek lands. The [[First Hellenic Republic|provisional government]] of the newly liberated Greece in the 19th century sent a delegation to Britain in search for living members or descendants of the Palaiologoi that could be offered the Greek throne and though the grave of Theodore Palaiologos in Landulph, Cornwall was noted, the delegation failed to find any living descendants.<ref name=\":12\"/> The noble who eventually was selected as the first King of Greece was [[Otto of Greece|Otto of Bavaria]] who through his ancestor [[John II, Duke of Bavaria]], was a descendant of the Laskaris dynasty (John being a great-great-great-grandson of Theodore I Laskaris through his daughter Maria Laskarina), the dynasty which the Palaiologoi had overthrown 571 years prior.\n\n== Family tree of the Palaiologoi (11th\u201316th century) ==\n{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree | | | | | Nik |Nik=[[Nikephoros Palaiologos|Nikephoros]]<br>duke of [[Mesopotamia (theme)|Mesopotamia]]}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree | | | | | Geo |Geo=[[George Palaiologos|Georgios]]<br>Palaiologos<br><small>\u221e Anna Doukaina<br>(grand-nephew of [[Constantine X Doukas]])}}\n{{familytree | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.}}\n{{familytree | Ale | | Nik | | And |Nik=Nikephoros|Ale=Alexios<br><small>\u221e Anna Komnene Doukaina|And=[[Andronikos Doukas Palaiologos|Andronikos]]<br>duke of Thessalonica<br><small>\u221e Komnene<br>(grand-daughter of [[Constantine X Doukas]])}}\n{{familytree | |!| | | |!}}\n{{familytree | Geo | | Mih |Mih=Michael|Geo=George<br>megas eteriarxes}}\n{{familytree | |!| | | |!}}\n{{familytree | Alx | | Ale |Alx=[[Alexios Palaiologos (despot)|Alexios]]<br>despot<br><small>~ Irene Angelina<br>(daughter [[Alexios III Angelos]])|Ale=Alexios<br>megas doux<br><small>\u221e Irene Komnene}}\n{{familytree | |!| | | |!}}\n{{familytree | The |~| And |~| unk |The=1.Teodora Palaiologina|And=[[Andronikos Palaiologos (megas domestikos)|Andronikos]]<br>megas domestikos|unk=2.(unknown)}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree | The |~| Mi8 | | Joh | | Con | | Mar | | Ire |Mi8=(1) [[Michael VIII Palaiologos|Michael VIII]]<br>Byzantine Emperor|The=Theodora Vatatzaina<br><small>(niece of [[John III Doukas Vatatzes|John III Vatatzes]])<br></small>[[Vatatzes|HOUSE OF VATATZES]]|Joh=(1) [[John Palaiologos (brother of Michael VIII)|John]]<br>megas domestikos<br><small>\u221e Tornikaina|Con=(2) [[Constantine Palaiologos (half-brother of Michael VIII)|Constantine]]<br><small>\u221e Irene Vranaina|Ire=Irene<br><small>\u221e John Kantakouzenos|Mar=Maria<br><small>\u221e Nikephoros Tarchaneiotes}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.}}\n{{familytree | | | | | An2 | | Ire | | Ann | | Eud | | The | | | | | | | | | | | | | | C