 Felger|website=cbslocal.com|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/baystateparent/docs/0612bsp |title=''BayStateParent Magazine''|date=June 2012|website=issuu.com|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nAlways considered a controversial sports-reporter, on October 12, 2011, Felger was involved in an online feud with [[Heidi Watney]], another local reporter, in which he claimed Watney had an affair with then [[Boston Red Sox]] catcher [[Jason Varitek]]. Watney responded via [[Twitter]] by questioning Felger's work ethic and integrity, and most media critics reprimanded Felger for being unprofessional.<ref>Hadfield, Ryan, [http://www.bostonsportsmedia.com/2011/10/sports-media-musings-the-sports-lodge-is-on-fire Sports Media Musings: The Sports Lodge Is On Fire!] ''Boston Sports Media Watch'', October 13, 2011</ref>\n\nOn November 8, 2017, Felger said on ''Felger and Massarotti'' that former [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher [[Roy Halladay]] was a \"moron\" for dying in a plane crash.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=O'Ryan|title=Michael Felger gets static over Roy Halladay rant|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/local_coverage/2017/11/michael_felger_gets_static_over_roy_halladay_rant|website=The Boston Herald|publisher=Herald Media|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> The comments led to a 3-day suspension from [[NBC Sports Boston]] (which runs a television simulcast of his radio show).<ref>{{cite web|author1=NBC Sports Boston|title=NBC Sports Boston on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/NBCSBoston/status/929062298806824965|website=Twitter|publisher=Twitter, Inc.|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> He apologized the next day on the air.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Antonio|first1=Planas|title=Michael Felger: 'What I've gotten, I deserve'|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/local_coverage/2017/11/michael_felger_apologizes_for_low_class_roy_halladay_comments|website=The Boston Herald|publisher=Herald Media|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Book==\n* ''Tales from the Patriots Sideline: A Collection of the Greatest Stories of the Team's First 40 Years'', authored by Michael Felger, foreword by [[Steve Grogan]], afterword by [[Bill Belichick]], pictures by [[Jim Mahoney]] of the ''[[Boston Herald]]'', {{ISBN|1-58261-525-X}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://boston.cbslocal.com/personality/mike-felger/ CBS Boston profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Felger, Michael}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Sportswriters from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American sports radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from Boston]]\n[[Category:Sports in Boston]]\n[[Category:Writers from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Communications alumni]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Boston Celtics broadcasters]]\n", "name_user": "Erictelevision", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Hyperlink)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Felger"}
{"title_page": "Sash of the Three Orders", "text_new": "{{short description|Presidential sash of Portugal}}\n{{Infobox order\n|title           = Sash of the Three Orders<br>''Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens''\n|image           = [[Image:Three Orders.jpg|250px|]]\n|caption         = Insignia of the order in 1918\n|awarded_by      = [[Image:Flag of Portugal.svg|18px]] [[Portuguese Republic]]\n|type            = [[Presidential sash|Presidential Sash and Breast Star]]\n|day             =\n|for             = exclusive use of the President of Portugal in office\n|motto           = \n|eligibility     = President of the Republic in office\n|head_title      = Grand Master\n|head            = [[President of Portugal|President of the Portuguese Republic]]\n|grades          = Grand Cross (BTO)<ref name=\"Republica01\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=154&list=1 |title= Chancelaria: entitades estrangeiras agraciadas com ordens Portuguesas|publisher=Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica |date=28 January 2017 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n|established     = 17 June 1789<ref name=\"Republica02\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=106 |title= Hist\u00f3ria da Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens |publisher=Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica |date=28 January 2017 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n|higher          = ''None''\n|lower           = [[Order of the Tower and Sword]]\n|image2          = [[Image:PRT Three Orders BAR.svg|90px]]\n|caption2        = Ribbon bar of the Sash of the Three Orders\n}}\n\nThe '''Sash of the Three Orders''' ({{lang-pt|Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens}}, or ''Banda da Gr\u00e3-Cruz das Tr\u00eas Ordens'') is a decoration that combines the insignia of the [[Grand Cross]]es of the Military Orders of [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|Christ]], [[Military Order of Aviz|Aviz]] and [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|St. James]]. It is the symbol of the [[President of the Portuguese Republic|Portuguese presidential]] magistracy, in their capacity as the [[Fount of honour|fount]] of the Portuguese [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Portugal|honours system]]; therefore, it cannot be conferred on nationals or foreigners, nor can it be used outside the exercise of office of the President. Unlike other decorations, the Sash is not granted to Presidents upon their inauguration, but rather only worn by them during their terms in office.<ref name=\"Republica03\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=105 |title= Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens|publisher=Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica |date=28 January 2017 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe decoration, along with the similar [[Sash of the Two Orders]], was officially founded in 1789 by [[Maria I of Portugal|Queen Maria I]].<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\">{{cite journal| url = http://www.conteudos.easysite.com.pt/files/48/ficheiros/emblematica/The_Three_Portuguese_Orders_of_Knightwood_OSMA__Medal_Notes_01_OCR.pdf | title = The Three Portugese Military Orders of Knighthood (1789-1910) | page = 15, 17-18 | author = Ant\u00f3nio M. Trigueiros & Gustav A. Tammann | year = 1997 | publisher = Orders and Medals Society of America | access-date = 21 March 2020}}</ref> However, its origins can be traced further back to 1551, when [[Pope Julius III]] issued the ''Praeclara Clarissimi'' [[Papal Bull]] of 30 November, surrendering his position as [[Grand Master (order)|Grand Master]] of the three Catholic knightly orders (the Order of Our Lord Jesus Christ, the Order of St. Benedict of Aviz, and the Order of Santiago) to [[John III of Portugal|King Jo\u00e3o III]] of the [[House of Aviz]], who proclaimed it hereditary in the Portuguese Crown.<ref name=\"Republica02\"/> Despite this, the [[List of Portuguese monarchs|monarchs]] often wore only the insignia of the Order of Christ.<ref name=\"Burke\">{{cite book|editor=[[Bernard Burke]]|title=The Book of Orders of Knighthood and Decorations of Honour|date=1858|publisher=Hurst & Blackett|location=London|page=186|chapter=Portugal|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/bookofordersofk00burk/page/186/mode/2up|}}</ref>\n\nIt was during the reign of Maria I that the orders were secularized from religious orders into military [[orders of merit]]; the queen further decreed that the insignia of all three orders were to be combined into one, to ensure that no one order was favored above the others.<ref name=\"Burke\"/> The Sash thus became a unique decoration worn by the monarch, distinguishing them as Grand Master of the Three Military Orders, along with all other Portuguese [[orders of chivalry]].<ref name=\"Republica03\"/> It was also entitled to be worn by the heir to the throne (titled [[Prince of Brazil]], and from 1815 [[Prince Royal of Portugal]]) as \"Grand Commander of the Three Orders\", and on occasion gifted to the consort of the monarch upon their marriage.<ref name=\"Agraciamentos\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9\u201310 |pages=4, 6 |doi= |access-date=23 March 2020 }}</ref> Other princes of the blood royal (''[[Infante of Portugal|Infante]]s'') belonging to the [[House of Braganza]], meanwhile, were entitled to wear the Sash of the Two Orders.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n\nDuring the era of the constitutional monarchy, it was customary to confer the Sash on foreign [[monarch]]s and [[Head of state|heads of state]] as a diplomatic gesture. After the [[5 October 1910 revolution|revolution of 1910]]&mdash;when the prerogative of Grand Master of the orders passed to the presidents of the Republic&mdash;the Sash was abolished in conjunction with the Ancient Military Orders, only to be restored in 1918. \n\n==Foreign awards==\n\nThe sash was awarded to various foreign Heads of State:<ref>\"[http://arquivo.presidencia.pt/details?id=37496 Banda da Gr\u00e3-Cruz das Tr\u00eas Ordens]\" (in Portuguese), ''Arquivo Hist\u00f3rico da Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica''. Retrieved 28 November 2019.</ref>\n* [[Albert I of Belgium|Albert I]], [[King of the Belgians]] (19 July 1919) \u2013 he was previously awarded the royal version of the Sash by his cousin, [[Manuel II of Portugal|King Manuel II of Portugal]], on 14 June 1910<ref name=\"Agraciamentos02\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9\u201310 |page=11 |doi= |access-date=23 March 2020 }}</ref>\n* [[Baudouin of Belgium|Baudouin]], [[King of the Belgians]] (14 March 1957)\n* [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]], [[King of Thailand]] (22 August 1960)\n* [[Charles II of Romania|Carol II]], [[King of Romania]] (18 October 1939)\n* [[Francisco Franco]], [[Caudillo|Caudillo of Spain]] (26 January 1962)\n* [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom]] (18 October 1955)\n* [[George V of the United Kingdom]] (1919)\n* [[George VI of the United Kingdom]] (2 May 1939)\n* [[Juscelino Kubitschek]], 21st President of Brazil (15 July 1957)\n* [[Leopold III of Belgium|Leopold III]], [[King of the Belgians]] (23 February 1938)\n* [[Haile Selassie]], [[Emperor of Ethiopia]] (10 August 1959)\n* [[Victor Emmanuel III]], [[King of Italy]] (1919)\n\nIn 1962, the Sash of the Three Orders was restricted to that of the President, and thus could no longer be granted to foreign Heads of State.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n\n== Insignia ==\n* The ''badge'' of the decoration is an oval in gold filigree, [[Enamel paint|enamelled]] white on both sides; before 1823, it was made of plain silver or gold with a blank reverse. The medallion depicts within three smaller ovals with the crosses of the three military orders: the order of Christ on top, the order of Aviz on the bottom left, and the order of St. James on the bottom right, each surmounted by a Heart of Jesus decoration. During the era of the monarchy, the badge was surmounted by the royal crown; after 1910 the crown was replaced by a [[laurel wreath]].<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n* The ''sash'' of the decoration is constituted of three equal stripes, its colors in the following order: green (Aviz), red (Christ), and violet (St. James); before 1796 the colors were red, green, and red.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n* The ''star'' of the decoration is a gilt circle in silver depicting the crosses of the three orders, superimposed on a splendor of 22 or 24 rays.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\nIn the official portraits of many of the Portuguese Heads of State from the 19th and 20th centuries, the Sash of the Three Orders, is one of the main piece represented:\n\n<gallery>\nFile:27- Rainha reinante D. Maria I - A Louca.jpg|[[Maria I of Portugal]], ''the Pious''\nFile:Jean-Baptiste Debret - Retrato de Dom Jo\u00e3o VI.jpg|[[John VI of Portugal]], ''the Clement''\nImage:Portrait of Dom Pedro, Duke of Bragan\u00e7a - Google Art Project edit.jpg|[[Pedro I of Brazil|Peter IV of Portugal & I of Brazil]], ''the Soldier King''\nImage:Queen Maria II by John Simpson.jpg|[[Maria II of Portugal]], ''the Educator''\nFile:FernandoIIPortugal.jpg|[[Fernando II of Portugal]], ''the Artist King''\nFile:D Pedro V.jpg|[[Peter V of Portugal]], ''the Hopeful''\nFile:Luis I.JPG|[[Lu\u00eds I of Portugal]], ''the Popular''\nFile:D. Carlos - A. Roque Gameiro (1902).png|[[Carlos I of Portugal]], ''the Diplomat''\nFile:35- Rei D. Manuel II - O Patriota.jpg|[[Manuel II of Portugal]], ''the Patriot''\nFile:Bernardino Machado com a Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens.png|Doctor [[Bernardino Machado]], 3rd and 8th President of Portugal\nFile:Antonio Jose Almeida 1919 cropped.jpg|Dr. [[Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 de Almeida]], 6th President of Portugal\nFile:Manuel Teixeira Gomes, 1923-11-03.png|[[Manuel Teixeira Gomes]], 7th President of Portugal\nFile:\u00d3scarCarmona(official).jpg|[[Marshal]] [[\u00d3scar Carmona]], 11th President of Portugal\nFile:AmericoThomaz.png|[[Admiral]] [[Am\u00e9rico Thomaz]], 13th President of Portugal\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/ Honorific orders of Portugal]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080629012451/http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/ordem_nacional_infante_lista.htm List of the Grand Collar of the Order of Infante D. Henrique]\n\n{{Orders, decorations and medals of Portugal}}\n\n[[Category:Orders, decorations, and medals of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Orders of chivalry awarded to heads of state, consorts and sovereign family members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Presidential sash of Portugal}}\n{{Infobox order\n|title           = Sash of the Three Orders<br>''Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens''\n|image           = [[Image:Three Orders.jpg|250px|]]\n|caption         = Insignia of the order in 1918\n|awarded_by      = [[Image:Flag of Portugal.svg|18px]] [[Portuguese Republic]]\n|type            = [[Presidential sash|Presidential Sash and Breast Star]]\n|day             =\n|for             = exclusive use of the President of Portugal in office\n|motto           = \n|eligibility     = President of the Republic in office\n|head_title      = Grand Master\n|head            = [[President of Portugal|President of the Portuguese Republic]]\n|grades          = Grand Cross (BTO)<ref name=\"Republica01\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=154&list=1 |title= Chancelaria: entitades estrangeiras agraciadas com ordens Portuguesas|publisher=Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica |date=28 January 2017 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n|established     = 17 June 1789<ref name=\"Republica02\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=106 |title= Hist\u00f3ria da Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens |publisher=Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica |date=28 January 2017 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n|higher          = ''None''\n|lower           = [[Order of the Tower and Sword]]\n|image2          = [[Image:PRT Three Orders BAR.svg|90px]]\n|caption2        = Ribbon bar of the Sash of the Three Orders\n}}\n\nThe '''Sash of the Three Orders''' ({{lang-pt|Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens}}, or ''Banda da Gr\u00e3-Cruz das Tr\u00eas Ordens'') is a decoration that combines the insignia of the [[Grand Cross]]es of the Military Orders of [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|Christ]], [[Military Order of Aviz|Aviz]] and [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|St. James]]. It is the symbol of the [[President of the Portuguese Republic|Portuguese presidential]] magistracy, in their capacity as the [[Fount of honour|fount]] of the Portuguese [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Portugal|honours system]]; therefore, it cannot be conferred on nationals or foreigners, nor can it be used outside the exercise of office of the President. Unlike other decorations, the Sash is not granted to Presidents upon their inauguration, but rather only worn by them during their terms in office.<ref name=\"Republica03\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=105 |title= Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens|publisher=Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica |date=28 January 2017 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe decoration, along with the similar [[Sash of the Two Orders]], was officially founded in 1789 by [[Maria I of Portugal|Queen Maria I]].<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\">{{cite journal| url = http://www.conteudos.easysite.com.pt/files/48/ficheiros/emblematica/The_Three_Portuguese_Orders_of_Knightwood_OSMA__Medal_Notes_01_OCR.pdf | title = The Three Portugese Military Orders of Knighthood (1789-1910) | page = 15, 17-18 | author = Ant\u00f3nio M. Trigueiros & Gustav A. Tammann | year = 1997 | publisher = Orders and Medals Society of America | access-date = 21 March 2020}}</ref> However, its origins can be traced further back to 1551, when [[Pope Julius III]] issued the ''Praeclara Clarissimi'' [[Papal Bull]] of 30 November, surrendering his position as [[Grand Master (order)|Grand Master]] of the three Catholic knightly orders (the Order of Our Lord Jesus Christ, the Order of St. Benedict of Aviz, and the Order of Santiago) to [[John III of Portugal|King Jo\u00e3o III]] of the [[House of Aviz]], who proclaimed it hereditary in the Portuguese Crown.<ref name=\"Republica02\"/> Despite this, the [[List of Portuguese monarchs|monarchs]] often wore only the insignia of the Order of Christ.<ref name=\"Burke\">{{cite book|editor=[[Bernard Burke]]|title=The Book of Orders of Knighthood and Decorations of Honour|date=1858|publisher=Hurst & Blackett|location=London|page=186|chapter=Portugal|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/bookofordersofk00burk/page/186/mode/2up|}}</ref>\n\nIt was during the reign of Maria I that the orders were secularized from religious orders into military [[orders of merit]]; the queen further decreed that the insignia of all three orders were to be combined into one, to ensure that no one order was favored above the others.<ref name=\"Burke\"/> The Sash thus became a unique decoration worn by the monarch, distinguishing them as Grand Master of the Three Military Orders, along with all other Portuguese [[orders of chivalry]].<ref name=\"Republica03\"/> It was also entitled to be worn by the heir to the throne (titled [[Prince of Brazil]], and from 1815 [[Prince Royal of Portugal]]) as \"Grand Commander of the Three Orders\", and on occasion gifted to the consort of the monarch upon their marriage.<ref name=\"Agraciamentos\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9\u201310 |pages=4, 6 |doi= |access-date=23 March 2020 }}</ref> Other princes of the blood royal (''[[Infante of Portugal|Infante]]s'') belonging to the [[House of Braganza]], meanwhile, were entitled to wear the Sash of the Two Orders.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n\nDuring the era of the constitutional monarchy, it was customary to confer the Sash on foreign [[monarch]]s and [[Head of state|heads of state]] as a diplomatic gesture. After the [[5 October 1910 revolution|revolution of 1910]]&mdash;when the prerogative of Grand Master of the orders passed to the presidents of the Republic&mdash;the Sash was abolished in conjunction with the Ancient Military Orders, only to be restored in 1918. \n\n==Foreign awards==\n\nThe sash was awarded to various foreign Heads of State:<ref>\"[http://arquivo.presidencia.pt/details?id=37496 Banda da Gr\u00e3-Cruz das Tr\u00eas Ordens]\" (in Portuguese), ''Arquivo Hist\u00f3rico da Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica''. Retrieved 28 November 2019.</ref>\n* [[Albert I of Belgium|Albert I]], [[King of the Belgians]] (19 July 1919) \u2013 he was previously awarded the royal version of the Sash by his cousin, [[Manuel II of Portugal|King Manuel II of Portugal]], on 14 June 1910<ref name=\"Agraciamentos02\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9\u201310 |page=11 |doi= |access-date=23 March 2020 }}</ref>\n* [[Baudouin of Belgium|Baudouin]], [[King of the Belgians]] (14 March 1957)\n* [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]], [[King of Thailand]] (22 August 1960)\n* [[Charles II of Romania|Carol II]], [[King of Romania]] (18 October 1939)\n* [[Francisco Franco]], [[Caudillo|Caudillo of Spain]] (26 January 1962)\n* [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom]] (18 October 1955)\n* [[George V of the United Kingdom]] (1919)\n* [[George VI of the United Kingdom]] (2 May 1939)\n* [[Juscelino Kubitschek]], 21st President of Brazil (15 July 1957)\n* [[Leopold III of Belgium|Leopold III]], [[King of the Belgians]] (23 February 1938)\n* [[Haile Selassie]], [[Emperor of Ethiopia]] (10 August 1959)\n* [[Victor Emmanuel III]], [[King of Italy]] (1919)\n\nIn 1962, the Sash of the Three Orders was restricted to that of the President, and thus could no longer be granted to foreign Heads of State.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n\n== Insignia ==\n* The ''badge'' of the decoration is an oval in gold filigree, [[enamelled]] white on both sides; before 1823, it was made of plain silver or gold with a blank reverse. The medallion depicts within three smaller ovals with the crosses of the three military orders: the order of Christ on top, the order of Aviz on the bottom left, and the order of St. James on the bottom right, each surmounted by a Heart of Jesus decoration. During the era of the monarchy, the badge was surmounted by the royal crown; after 1910 the crown was replaced by a [[laurel wreath]].<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n* The ''sash'' of the decoration is constituted of three equal stripes, its colors in the following order: green (Aviz), red (Christ), and violet (St. James); before 1796 the colors were red, green, and red.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n* The ''star'' of the decoration is a gilt circle in silver depicting the crosses of the three orders, superimposed on a splendor of 22 or 24 rays.<ref name=\"Trig&Tamm\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\nIn the official portraits of many of the Portuguese Heads of State from the 19th and 20th centuries, the Sash of the Three Orders, is one of the main piece represented:\n\n<gallery>\nFile:27- Rainha reinante D. Maria I - A Louca.jpg|[[Maria I of Portugal]], ''the Pious''\nFile:Jean-Baptiste Debret - Retrato de Dom Jo\u00e3o VI.jpg|[[John VI of Portugal]], ''the Clement''\nImage:Portrait of Dom Pedro, Duke of Bragan\u00e7a - Google Art Project edit.jpg|[[Pedro I of Brazil|Peter IV of Portugal & I of Brazil]], ''the Soldier King''\nImage:Queen Maria II by John Simpson.jpg|[[Maria II of Portugal]], ''the Educator''\nFile:FernandoIIPortugal.jpg|[[Fernando II of Portugal]], ''the Artist King''\nFile:D Pedro V.jpg|[[Peter V of Portugal]], ''the Hopeful''\nFile:Luis I.JPG|[[Lu\u00eds I of Portugal]], ''the Popular''\nFile:D. Carlos - A. Roque Gameiro (1902).png|[[Carlos I of Portugal]], ''the Diplomat''\nFile:35- Rei D. Manuel II - O Patriota.jpg|[[Manuel II of Portugal]], ''the Patriot''\nFile:Bernardino Machado com a Banda das Tr\u00eas Ordens.png|Doctor [[Bernardino Machado]], 3rd and 8th President of Portugal\nFile:Antonio Jose Almeida 1919 cropped.jpg|Dr. [[Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 de Almeida]], 6th President of Portugal\nFile:Manuel Teixeira Gomes, 1923-11-03.png|[[Manuel Teixeira Gomes]], 7th President of Portugal\nFile:\u00d3scarCarmona(official).jpg|[[Marshal]] [[\u00d3scar Carmona]], 11th President of Portugal\nFile:AmericoThomaz.png|[[Admiral]] [[Am\u00e9rico Thomaz]], 13th President of Portugal\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/ Honorific orders of Portugal]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080629012451/http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/ordem_nacional_infante_lista.htm 